  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Weaver et al. (1977)</h1>

    <div class="stub-banner">⚠️ <strong>Stub</strong> — content pending analysis</div>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Weaver et al. 1977</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Paper</td></tr>
        <tr><th>DOI:</th><td><a href="https://doi.org/10.1086/155692">10.1086/155692</a></td></tr>
        <tr><th>Topic:</th><td>Interstellar bubble dynamics; wind-blown bubble self-similar solutions</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Weaver et al. (1977)</strong> developed the classic analytic model for the structure and evolution of interstellar bubbles driven by stellar winds. The self-similar scalings derived in this work (e.g., radius ∝ t<sup>3/5</sup>) are widely used as analogies for jet–cocoon expansion in astrophysical jet theory.</p>

    <h2>Relevance to ArXiv Atlas</h2>
    <p>Cited by <WikiLink slug="pages/2603.16647" text="Peretti et al. (2603.16647)" /> as the origin of the t<sup>3/5</sup> self-similar scaling applied to cocoon expansion around sub-relativistic jets.</p>

    <h2>See also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/jet-cocoon-systems" text="Jet–Cocoon systems" /></li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Bromberg_2011" text="Bromberg et al. (2011)" /></li>
    </ul>
  </main>
</Base>
